246 523 1192 (Title:          Are comparators held by value or by reference?) 1192 SB
246 579 857 (Sections:       23.1.2 [lib.associative.reqmts]) 857 SB
246 635 377 (Status:         Active) 377 SB
246 691 273 (  Description:) 273 SB
396 803 1311 (Are containers supposed to hold compare functions as values or) 1311 SB
396 859 281 (as references?) 281 SB
396 971 1150 (Again, I couldn't find anything in the draft that specifies) 1150 SB
396 1027 1123 (whether compare functions of a container are values or) 1123 SB
396 1083 1224 (references internally, which of course makes a difference for) 1224 SB
396 1139 176 (the user.) 176 SB
396 1251 1198 (The fact that the compare functions are constant references) 1198 SB
396 1307 1260 (when provided to a container constructor seems to imply that) 1260 SB
396 1363 1224 (they are internally held as references.  Hence the user has to) 1224 SB
396 1419 1024 (pay attention to the lifetime of the compare object.) 1024 SB
396 1531 1262 (On the other hand, the container constructors have a compare) 1262 SB
396 1587 1361 (parameter which is defaulted by a temporary object. This gives the) 1361 SB
396 1643 1387 (impression that the compare parameter will probably be copied and) 1387 SB
396 1699 1325 (internally held as a value.  In this case the user cannot work with) 1325 SB
396 1755 1318 (polymorphic function objects because of the inevitable slicing, or) 1318 SB
396 1811 517 (has to find workarounds.) 517 SB
396 1923 1390 (In any case, the users needs to know what the exact requirements to) 1390 SB
396 1979 1070 (the compare function of an associative container are.) 1070 SB
246 2091 437 (Proposed Resolution:) 437 SB
